  "opinion": "As a 66-year-old carpenter living in Bologna, I spend about an hour daily on social media, mostly to stay connected with my two children and share my hobbies like yoga and painting. Dealing with fake content is something I've learned to handle through simple, practical steps. First, I always check the source of information. If it's from a well-known news outlet or a trusted friend, I'm more likely to believe it. But if it's from an unfamiliar page or someone I don't know, I take it with a grain of salt. My primary school education taught me to be cautious, and my moderate openness means I'm willing to learn but not too quick to trust everything I see. I also rely on my children for advice; they're more tech-savvy and help me spot scams or false stories. For example, when I see posts about health remedies or political claims, I ask them or look it up on reliable websites before sharing. My Islamic beliefs emphasize truthfulness, so I avoid spreading misinformation. I use social media sparingly, focusing on positive interactions like sharing travel photos or yoga tips, which keeps me away from harmful content. To manage fake content, I report suspicious posts to the platform and unfollow accounts that consistently share falsehoods. My low conscientiousness means I'm not overly organized, but I've set a simple rule: think twice before clicking or sharing. This approach helps me enjoy social media without stress, aligning with my good mental health and moderate neuroticism. In short, staying skeptical, seeking help from trusted people, and prioritizing real connections over viral content work best for me.",
